The paper introduces a generative formulation of the linear archetype model, parameterized by neural networks, which suggests that it belongs to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also explores the archetypes of female facial expressions, which suggests that it belongs to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper uses side information to learn an optimal representation, which suggests that it belongs to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and computational linguistics (cs.CL) sub-categories. Finally, the paper explores the chemical space of small organic molecules, which suggests that it belongs to the software engineering (cs.SD) sub-category.
